{{rfv}}
{{wikipediapar|Macaca (slur)}}

===Etymology===
From French ''[[macaque]]'' < Portuguese ''[[macaco]]'' (monkey) < Bantu.

===Noun===
{{en-noun-reg}}

#{{italbrac|racial slur}} A [[derogatory]] [[epithet]] for dark-skinned people who appear to be of Middle-Eastern descent. ['''''Citation needed''''']
#:''"Well I guess this is my '''macaca''' payback."'' —Jim Webb <ref>[http://www.c-span.org/VideoArchives.asp?z1=&PopupMenu_Name=Politics/Elections&CatCodePairs=Issue,PE;], James H. Webb; prefacing his answer to a question about his former anti-female statements. ''C-SPAN'' (video recording 59:04/1:11:26) Monday, September 18, [[2006]] (RealPlayer format).  The most contemporary usage of the word, made in the presence of many professional writers.</ref>, and
#:''"Let's give a welcome to '''macaca''', here."''—George Allen <ref>[http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/08/14/AR2006081400589.html], Senator George Allen; referring to an opposition candidate's supporter who followed Allen everwhere. ''Washington Post'' Tuesday, August 15, [[2006]]</ref>
#{{archaic}} {{slang}} {{italbrac|racial slur}} A dismissive epithet used by French-speaking colonials in Central Africa to refer to a native of the Congo or persons of native Congo ethnicity.
#{{rfv-sense}} {{slang}} (''contemporary usage'') An [[embarrassment]] or [[embarrassing]] [[moment]].

